data.content:
Your test works but `Assert.IsTrue` gives unhelpful failure messages (just "Expected: True, Actual: False"). MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions with clear diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.Contains(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` |

Other useful collection assertions:
- `Assert.Contains(item, collection)` — verifies item exists
- `Assert.DoesNotContain(item, collection)`
- `Assert.ContainsSingle(collection)` — asserts exactly one element and returns it
- `Assert.IsEmpty(collection)`

These give failure messages like *"Expected collection to have 3 elements but has 2"* instead of just *"Assert.IsTrue failed"*.
